<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870623-0003 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 06/23/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   THE DOLLAR RALLIED, reaching three-month highs against the British pound and German mark. The stronger U.S. currency helped send commodity prices plunging and sparked gains by bonds and stocks. Bonds also rose on heavy Japanese buying as Tokyo stocks and bonds skidded. The Dow Jones industrials gained 24.66, to a record 2445.51.    ---   The NASD's new president is expected to be Joseph Hardiman, a top executive at Alex. Brown andamp; Sons of Baltimore and the current chairman of the over-the-counter regulatory group, according to sources.    ---   The SEC is expected to propose today a rule that would force public companies that are changing auditors to disclose when and why they have &quot;shopped&quot; for favorable opinions. Many firms oppose such a rule.    ---   JWT Group has attracted another possible suitor, an affiliate of British andamp; Commonwealth Holdings. New York-based JWT already is considering a $515 million takeover bid from WPP Group as well as alternatives.    ---   Saatchi andamp; Saatchi plans to merge two U.S.-based advertising agencies. The move is an attempt by Saatchi to streamline various agencies acquired during the past two years.    ---   Burlington Industries and Morgan Stanley won court rulings that probably will force Asher Edelman and Dominion Textile to abandon their joint takeover bid for Burlington.    ---   American Brands agreed to buy ACCO World Corp., an office-supply concern, for $29 a share, or $602 million. The purchase continues American Brands' aggressive acquisition of consumer-products lines.    ---   Harcourt won a court victory tied to debenture conversion rights, repelling a move that could have derailed its $3 billion recapitalization plan.    ---   Britain plans to sell up to 25% of a state-owned airport operator in an innovative tender offer, but sell the rest under the fixed-price method.    ---   The Supreme Court left intact a lower court ruling allowing banks to sell commercial paper for clients. But the case has been overshadowed by the Fed's decision to let banking units underwrite such securities.    ---   Dayton Hudson's request for stiffer Minnesota anti-takeover laws may lead to legislation as early as this week, state political leaders said.    ---   A group of Gillette shareholders asked a judge to overturn a 1986 accord barring Revlon from making a new takeover bid for Gillette.    ---   Akzo agreed to buy the specialtychemical business of Stauffer Chemical from ICI for $625 million.    ---   Four big European airlines plan to develop a joint computer-reservation system to prevent U.S. booking systems from dominating the market.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 178,210,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2445.51, up 24.66; transportation 1027.20, up 0.26; utilities 206.76, up 1.21.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Treasury index 1315.94, up 8.13.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 122.72, off 2.57; spot index 126.66, off 1.71.    Dollar: 146.20 yen, up 1.37; 1.8465 marks, up 0.0169. </TEXT></DOC>